9
00:00:53,454 --> 00:00:55,988
   industrial pasta machines    
        produce noodles         

10
00:00:55,990 --> 00:00:58,858
       by extruding dough       
        through a die.          

11
00:00:58,860 --> 00:01:00,526
   the die has holes in it,     

12
00:01:00,528 --> 00:01:04,062
  which are shaped to produce   
   a specific type of pasta.    

13
00:01:04,064 --> 00:01:05,797
       as the dough comes       
       through the holes        

14
00:01:05,799 --> 00:01:07,532
    in a continuous stream,     

15
00:01:07,534 --> 00:01:10,636
     a knife cuts the pasta     
    to the correct length.      

16
00:01:13,674 --> 00:01:16,809
   this industrial pasta die    
       produces fusilli,        

17
00:01:16,811 --> 00:01:20,212
      up to one and a half      
     tons of it per hour.       

18
00:01:20,214 --> 00:01:22,815
   and this is just a midsize   
              die.              

19
00:01:22,817 --> 00:01:27,153
  the largest ones can produce  
 four tons of pasta per hour.   

20
00:01:27,155 --> 00:01:31,023
     the die block is made      
  of a bronze-aluminum alloy.   

21
00:01:31,025 --> 00:01:34,293
   a computer-guided machine    
   drills holes for inserts     

22
00:01:34,295 --> 00:01:37,162
 through which the pasta dough  
       will be extruded.        

23
00:01:37,164 --> 00:01:39,632
     the front of the block     
     is then chrome plated      

24
00:01:39,634 --> 00:01:41,566
           to protect           
    against the sharp knife     

25
00:01:41,568 --> 00:01:44,637
     that cuts the extruded     
      pasta off the die.        

26
00:01:44,639 --> 00:01:47,106
    the next step is to make    
            inserts             

27
00:01:47,108 --> 00:01:49,775
      that go in the holes      
         in the block.          

28
00:01:49,777 --> 00:01:52,845
     an insert is comprised     
   of male and female parts     

29
00:01:52,847 --> 00:01:55,915
and a nonstick plastic lining.  

30
00:01:55,917 --> 00:01:58,184
     a computer-guided mill     
       cuts the linings         

31
00:01:58,186 --> 00:02:02,254
          from a plate          
     of nonstick plastic.       

32
00:02:02,256 --> 00:02:03,588
 another computer-guided mill   

33
00:02:03,590 --> 00:02:06,191
            machines            
the female part of the inserts  

34
00:02:06,193 --> 00:02:09,629
     in a more than quarter     
 of an inch-thick brass plate.  

35
00:02:13,668 --> 00:02:17,336
 then a worker places a lining  
     in each female part.       

36
00:02:22,343 --> 00:02:27,279
    he taps it into position    
   with a mallet and punch.     

37
00:02:27,281 --> 00:02:29,748
         the plate then         
    goes back on the mill,      

38
00:02:29,750 --> 00:02:32,618
    which cuts an extrusion     
      slot in the lining.       

39
00:02:32,620 --> 00:02:37,490
   the slot shape determines    
       the pasta shape.         

40
00:02:37,492 --> 00:02:40,025
        a mill machines         
 the male part of the inserts   

41
00:02:40,027 --> 00:02:43,429
    in another brass plate.     

42
00:02:43,431 --> 00:02:46,231
       a worker detaches        
 the male parts from the plate  

43
00:02:46,233 --> 00:02:49,568
   with a punch and mallet.     

44
00:02:49,570 --> 00:02:53,205
  he detaches the lined female  
      parts the same way.       

45
00:02:58,112 --> 00:03:00,579
   then he assembles the male   
       and female parts         

46
00:03:00,581 --> 00:03:04,750
 by forcing one onto the other  
    with the help of a steel    
             punch.             

47
00:03:12,060 --> 00:03:15,327
   he finishes the die insert   
 by cutting off the protruding  

48
00:03:15,329 --> 00:03:17,329
  excess plastic with a blade   

49
00:03:17,331 --> 00:03:19,765
       so that the lining       
    is flush with the top.      

50
00:03:23,270 --> 00:03:25,337
 the factory makes die inserts  

51
00:03:25,339 --> 00:03:27,405
        in thousands of         
      different shapes --       

52
00:03:27,407 --> 00:03:28,874
        some standard,          

53
00:03:28,876 --> 00:03:32,078
     others in the client's     
   custom-made pasta shape.     

54
00:03:35,349 --> 00:03:38,617
   this computer-guided lathe   
              makes             
      brass locking rings       

55
00:03:38,619 --> 00:03:41,053
       which will secure        
   the inserts in the block.    

56
00:03:53,367 --> 00:03:56,235
  now, final assembly begins.   

57
00:03:56,237 --> 00:03:58,770
        a worker places         
     the block face-down,       

58
00:03:58,772 --> 00:04:00,105
    and from the back drops     

59
00:04:00,107 --> 00:04:03,042
      an insert top-first       
        into each hole.         

60
00:04:06,781 --> 00:04:10,182
   next, he places a locking    
      ring in each hole.        

61
00:04:18,092 --> 00:04:20,593
     then, with a hydraulic     
       press and punch,         

62
00:04:20,595 --> 00:04:23,796
   he forces down each locking  
              ring              
    to within approximately     

63
00:04:23,798 --> 00:04:26,565
          1 millimeter          
   of the insert underneath.    

64
00:04:33,140 --> 00:04:36,675
   in this position, the ring   
              holds             
    the insert in the hole      

65
00:04:36,677 --> 00:04:41,079
     but doesn't prevent it     
from spinning within the hole.  

66
00:04:41,081 --> 00:04:44,416
         the next step          
   is to adjust the inserts     

67
00:04:44,418 --> 00:04:47,286
         to make their          
     orientation uniform.       

68
00:04:47,288 --> 00:04:50,489
        he inserts a pin        
    into each insert slot.      

69
00:04:50,491 --> 00:04:53,626
    then he rotates the pin     
     to rotate the insert.      

70
00:04:53,628 --> 00:04:56,361
  once the insert orientation   
          is correct,           

71
00:04:56,363 --> 00:04:57,762
  he forces the locking ring    

72
00:04:57,764 --> 00:05:02,234
        down all the way        
   to immobilize the insert.    

73
00:05:02,236 --> 00:05:05,103
  once he has all the inserts   
    oriented the same way,      

74
00:05:05,105 --> 00:05:07,973
   he sands the chrome-plated   
       front of the die,        

75
00:05:07,975 --> 00:05:11,310
first with a medium-grit disk,  

76
00:05:11,312 --> 00:05:14,046
      then with a fine-grit     
           sandpaper.           

77
00:05:14,048 --> 00:05:18,049
 the die surface must be smooth 
     as silk for the knife      

78
00:05:18,051 --> 00:05:22,254
          to slice off          
  the extruded pasta cleanly.   

79
00:05:22,256 --> 00:05:26,458
 he verifies the width of every 
 extrusion slot with a gauge.   

80
00:05:26,460 --> 00:05:28,860
          this ensures          
     every piece of pasta       

81
00:05:28,862 --> 00:05:31,096
will be the correct thickness.  

82
00:05:34,134 --> 00:05:36,335
        then on the back        
     of the finished die,       

83
00:05:36,337 --> 00:05:39,805
           he stamps            
   the manufacturer's name.     

84
00:05:39,807 --> 00:05:43,475
 the die is ready to be mounted 
   on an industrial machine     

85
00:05:43,477 --> 00:05:45,678
      that extrudes dough       
    into perfectly shaped,      

86
00:05:45,680 --> 00:05:47,947
     ready-to-boil pasta.       

